<subSubSection pageId="58" pageNumber="59" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,151,1760]" box="[199,536,620,645]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,412,620,645]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Description. Male</emphasis>
(
<typeStatus box="[427,528,620,645]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">holotype</typeStatus>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,151,1760]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">MEASUREMENTS. Total body length 6.0, carapace width 2.2. Distance PME-PME 150 µm, diameter PME 200 µm, distance PME-ALE 170 µm, distance AME-AME 30 µm, diameter AME 70 µm. Sternum width/length: 1.6/ 1.2. Leg 1: 83.2 (19.5 + 0.9 + 20.0 + 37.7 + 5.1), tibia 2: 14.4, tibia 3: 9.3, tibia 4: 13.7; tibia 1 L/d: 98. Femora 1– 4 width (at half length): 0.28, 0.35, 0.32, 0.30.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,151,1760]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<collectionCode box="[199,278,800,824]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">COLOR</collectionCode>
(in ethanol). Carapace ochre-yellow with large brown median mark including posterior part of ocular area; sternum ochre to light brown; legs brown, tips of femora and tibiae lighter (whitish), without dark rings; abdomen greenish gray, dorsally and laterally densely covered with dark marks, ventrally with light brown area in front of gonopore, very indistinct plate in front of spinnerets.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,151,1760]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<collectionCode box="[199,264,944,967]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">BODY</collectionCode>
. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[446,546,943,968]" captionStart="FIGURES 138–149" captionStartId="39.[151,264,1844,1866]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,625,1822]" captionTargetId="figure@39.[151,1436,625,1822]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 138–149. Live specimens, Mesabolivar togatus group. 138–139. M. togatus (Keyserling, 1891), males from Sooretama (with Arachnocoris bug; arrow) and Santa Maria Madalena. 140. M. baianus sp. n., male from Serra Bonita. 141– 142. M. similis sp. n., male and female from Morro de Pedra.143–144. M. buraquinho sp. n., male from Bonito, female from Mata do Buraquinho.145–146.M.caiporaHuber, 2015,male and femalefrom Serra daItabaiana.147. M.inmanis sp. n., male from Vargem Alta.148–149.M.cyaneomaculatus (Keyserling, 1891), males from Penedo." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202553/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 147</figureCitation>
, very similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Keyserling" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[743,978,943,968]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Mesabolivar" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyaneomaculatus">
<emphasis box="[743,978,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">M. cyaneomaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(cf. 
<figureCitation box="[1038,1199,943,968]" captionStart="FIGURES 138–149" captionStartId="39.[151,264,1844,1866]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,625,1822]" captionTargetId="figure@39.[151,1436,625,1822]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 138–149. Live specimens, Mesabolivar togatus group. 138–139. M. togatus (Keyserling, 1891), males from Sooretama (with Arachnocoris bug; arrow) and Santa Maria Madalena. 140. M. baianus sp. n., male from Serra Bonita. 141– 142. M. similis sp. n., male and female from Morro de Pedra.143–144. M. buraquinho sp. n., male from Bonito, female from Mata do Buraquinho.145–146.M.caiporaHuber, 2015,male and femalefrom Serra daItabaiana.147. M.inmanis sp. n., male from Vargem Alta.148–149.M.cyaneomaculatus (Keyserling, 1891), males from Penedo." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202553/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Figs 148–149</figureCitation>
); ocular area raised; carapace with distinct median furrow; clypeus unmodified; sternum unmodified.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,151,1760]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
CHELICERAE. With two pairs of frontal apophyses, proximal pair very small and rounded, distal pair near median line, pointed and very thin in frontal view (
<figureCitation box="[722,881,1052,1077]" captionStart="FIGURES 215–222" captionStartId="56.[151,264,1595,1617]" captionTargetBox="[165,1417,193,1570]" captionTargetId="figure@56.[151,1436,193,1574]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="FIGURES 215–222. Mesabolivar madalena sp. n. (215–218, ZFMK Ar 19071) and M. inmanis sp. n. (219–222, ZFMK Ar 19072). 215–216, 219–220. Male chelicerae, frontal and lateral views. 217–218, 221–222. Tips of left procursi, prolateral and dorsal views. Scale lines: 0.5 (215–216, 219–220, all chelicerae at same scale), 0.3 (217–218, 221–222; all procursi at same scale)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202573/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Figs 219–220</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,151,1760]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<collectionCode box="[199,268,1088,1111]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">PALPS</collectionCode>
. In general very similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Keyserling" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[593,827,1087,1112]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Mesabolivar" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyaneomaculatus">
<emphasis box="[593,827,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">M. cyaneomaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(cf. Huber 2000: figs 813, 816), proximal segments apparently identical in shape but larger (femur length 0.77 vs. 
<quantity box="[854,995,1124,1149]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7779999999999998" metricValueMax="1.8542" metricValueMin="1.7018" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" unit="in" value="0.7" valueMax="0.73" valueMin="0.67">0.67–0.73 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Keyserling" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[1002,1234,1124,1149]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Mesabolivar" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyaneomaculatus">
<emphasis box="[1002,1234,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">M. cyaneomaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); procursus distal part (
<figureCitation box="[209,365,1159,1184]" captionStart="FIGURES 215–222" captionStartId="56.[151,264,1595,1617]" captionTargetBox="[165,1417,193,1570]" captionTargetId="figure@56.[151,1436,193,1574]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="FIGURES 215–222. Mesabolivar madalena sp. n. (215–218, ZFMK Ar 19071) and M. inmanis sp. n. (219–222, ZFMK Ar 19072). 215–216, 219–220. Male chelicerae, frontal and lateral views. 217–218, 221–222. Tips of left procursi, prolateral and dorsal views. Scale lines: 0.5 (215–216, 219–220, all chelicerae at same scale), 0.3 (217–218, 221–222; all procursi at same scale)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202573/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Figs 221–222</figureCitation>
) and bulbal process very similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Keyserling" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[766,997,1159,1184]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Mesabolivar" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyaneomaculatus">
<emphasis box="[766,997,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">M. cyaneomaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[1052,1207,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Huber" authorityYear="2018" box="[1052,1203,1159,1184]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Mesabolivar" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="madalena">M. madalena</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,151,1760]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<collectionCode box="[199,258,1197,1220]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">LEGS</collectionCode>
. Without spines, without curved hairs, few vertical hairs; retrolateral trichobothrium on tibia 1 at 2.5%; prolateral trichobothrium present on tibia 1; tarsus 1 with&gt;50 pseudosegments, distally fairly distinct.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,151,1760]" box="[199,1388,1268,1293]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,260,1268,1293]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Male</emphasis>
(variation). Tibia 
<quantity box="[464,507,1268,1293]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" unit="in" value="1.0">1 in</quantity>
five other males: 16.9–17.6 (mean 17.4). Some males with lighter brown legs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,151,1760]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,293,1303,1328]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Female.</emphasis>
In general similar to male but all leg femora approximately same width. Tibia 
<quantity box="[1184,1228,1303,1328]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" unit="in" value="1.0">1 in</quantity>
<specimenCount box="[1235,1363,1303,1328]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" type="female">12 females</specimenCount>
: 13.2– 16.4 (mean 14.3). Epigynum as in 
<figureCitation box="[553,656,1340,1365]" captionStart="FIGURES 223–226" captionStartId="57.[151,264,1180,1202]" captionTargetBox="[154,1436,195,1158]" captionTargetId="figure@57.[151,1436,193,1159]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURES 223–226. Mesabolivar madalena sp. n. (223–224, ZFMK Ar 19071) and M. inmanis sp. n. (225–226, ZFMK Ar 19072). 223, 225. Epigyna, ventral views. 224, 226. Cleared female genitalia, dorsal views (arrow points at V-shaped sclerite). Scale lines:0.5." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202575/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Figs 225</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[669,714,1340,1364]" captionStart="FIGURES241–252" captionStartId="61.[151,264,1628,1650]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1607]" captionTargetId="figure@61.[151,1436,193,1607]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURES241–252. Femaleepigyna in ventral views and cleared female genitalia in dorsal views, Mesabolivar togatus group (part2). 241–242.M.bico sp. n. (ZFMK Ar19065).243–244.M.mimoso sp. n. (ZFMK Ar 19069).245–246. M.madalenasp. n. (ZFMK Ar 19071). 247–248. M. inmanis sp. n. (ZFMK Ar 19072). 249. M. sp. (“sp. 7” in Astrin et al. 2006) (Br03/100- 14b). 250.M.cyaneomaculatus (Keyserling, 1891) (ZFMK Ar 19075). 251–252.M. claricae sp. n. (ZFMK Ar 19083)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202579/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">247</figureCitation>
; anterior plate semicircular, without processes, with distinctive shape of posterior margin (with pair of projections), median pocket close to posterior margin; simple large posterior plate. Internal genitalia as in 
<figureCitation box="[495,599,1412,1437]" captionStart="FIGURES 223–226" captionStartId="57.[151,264,1180,1202]" captionTargetBox="[154,1436,195,1158]" captionTargetId="figure@57.[151,1436,193,1159]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURES 223–226. Mesabolivar madalena sp. n. (223–224, ZFMK Ar 19071) and M. inmanis sp. n. (225–226, ZFMK Ar 19072). 223, 225. Epigyna, ventral views. 224, 226. Cleared female genitalia, dorsal views (arrow points at V-shaped sclerite). Scale lines:0.5." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202575/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Figs 226</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[614,659,1412,1436]" captionStart="FIGURES241–252" captionStartId="61.[151,264,1628,1650]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1607]" captionTargetId="figure@61.[151,1436,193,1607]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURES241–252. Femaleepigyna in ventral views and cleared female genitalia in dorsal views, Mesabolivar togatus group (part2). 241–242.M.bico sp. n. (ZFMK Ar19065).243–244.M.mimoso sp. n. (ZFMK Ar 19069).245–246. M.madalenasp. n. (ZFMK Ar 19071). 247–248. M. inmanis sp. n. (ZFMK Ar 19072). 249. M. sp. (“sp. 7” in Astrin et al. 2006) (Br03/100- 14b). 250.M.cyaneomaculatus (Keyserling, 1891) (ZFMK Ar 19075). 251–252.M. claricae sp. n. (ZFMK Ar 19083)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202579/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">248</figureCitation>
, without V-shaped sclerite, pair of large pore-plates in tent-shaped lateral position, converging dorsally, outer margins diverging anteriorly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,151,1760]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,390,1484,1509]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Natural history.</emphasis>
Most specimens were found in a cave, among rocks and on the cave roof. Outside the cave they built their webs in sheltered spaces under large rocks.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="58" pageNumber="59" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,151,1760]" box="[199,1180,1556,1581]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1556,1581]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known from 
<typeStatus box="[510,558,1557,1581]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">type</typeStatus>
locality in 
<collectingRegion box="[685,845,1556,1581]" country="Brazil" name="Espirito Santo" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Espírito Santo</collectingRegion>
state (
<collectingCountry box="[917,989,1556,1581]" name="Brazil" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Brazil</collectingCountry>
) only (
<figureCitation box="[1069,1168,1556,1581]" captionStart="FIGURES726–729" captionStartId="164.[151,264,1408,1430]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1386]" captionTargetId="figure@164.[151,1436,193,1386]" captionTargetPageId="164" captionText="FIGURES726–729. Knowndistribution of the Mesabolivar togatusgroup.“?”: dubious recordsof M.togatus, possible record of M. baianus (sub. M. togatus in Machado 2007), and of M. cyaneomaculatus from Paraná (Mello-Leitão 1947b); asterisk: erroneous record of M.togatusfrom Pará in Mello-Leitão (1940a).TL, type locality." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202701/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 727</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,151,1760]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,255,1591,1616]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Note</emphasis>
. Astrin 
<emphasis box="[344,400,1591,1616]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">et al.</emphasis>
(2006) sequenced CO1 of a female specimen from Parque Estadual de Cantareira (
<geoCoordinate box="[1324,1431,1592,1616]" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" precision="55" value="-23.417">23.417°S</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[151,269,1628,1653]" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" precision="55" value="-46.617">46.617°W</geoCoordinate>
), named “sp. 7” (
<collectionCode box="[466,548,1628,1652]" country="Germany" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34613" name="Zoologisches Forschungsmuseum Alexander Koenig" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">ZFMK</collectionCode>
, Br03/100-14b). The epigynum of this specimen closely resembles the present species (
<figureCitation box="[253,356,1663,1688]" captionStart="FIGURES241–252" captionStartId="61.[151,264,1628,1650]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1607]" captionTargetId="figure@61.[151,1436,193,1607]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURES241–252. Femaleepigyna in ventral views and cleared female genitalia in dorsal views, Mesabolivar togatus group (part2). 241–242.M.bico sp. n. (ZFMK Ar19065).243–244.M.mimoso sp. n. (ZFMK Ar 19069).245–246. M.madalenasp. n. (ZFMK Ar 19071). 247–248. M. inmanis sp. n. (ZFMK Ar 19072). 249. M. sp. (“sp. 7” in Astrin et al. 2006) (Br03/100- 14b). 250.M.cyaneomaculatus (Keyserling, 1891) (ZFMK Ar 19075). 251–252.M. claricae sp. n. (ZFMK Ar 19083)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202579/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 249</figureCitation>
). However, considering the large geographic distance (
<quantity box="[1009,1103,1663,1688]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.7" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" unit="km" value="670.0">670 km</quantity>
) and the absence of further specimens from intermediate localities, this female is here not assigned to the present species but interpreted as representing a different, undescribed species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
